I hope everybody is having a fresh start to 2023 after holiday hibernation. 

The best memory of 2022 for me was moving to Pacific Northwest from Los Angeles. That sense of adventure and reinventing myself made life feel like it was moving forwards again. The small city with kind down to earth people and endless lush greenery. 

I talk a lot with my clients about their life situations, hopes and dreams. There is a common thread many express and that is a wish for change. If there is anything I can give as an advice it is that life is surprisingly short and frail. Sometimes big changes can feel like a mountain to climb, but from those changes you can push the glass ceiling of personal growth higher.

Moving on and moving forwards in life is possible for us all. I have traveled my entire life alone and moved to new countries with only a handful of cash. I’ve learned the visa systems and played it to my advantage. If you are reading this it means you have a device connected to the internet. That is a privilege that allows you to research and find your own pathway to brighter future. Don’t be afraid of downgrading your life for a moment as you will build yourself back up again. And more importantly don’t fear loneliness; it is an opportunity to open yourself up to new people, cultures and experiences that grow you as a person. 

Make this the year that you leave your comfort zone and find yourself. Whether it is where you are now or if it means taking a larger leap to embark on an adventure. 

Best of luck 🖤

Tattooing has been practiced for thousands of years within various cultures. The rise of more “modern” contemporary tattooing, that we these days can put in the category of American traditional tattooing didn’t start until the second half of the 1800s. This was largely due to Captain James Cook’s voyages to the pacific islands such as Hawaii where the Royal Navy sailors were introduced to the Polynesian tattooing. 

As tattooing spread among sailor, the designs started developing a meaning behind them. The crossed cannons meant that you were a veteran or in active military service as a sailor. The nautical star become a representation of the compass rose - A symbol of finding your way back home. The most common of these all, the swallows indicated that per bird the sailor had traveled 5000 nautical miles (roughly 5754 miles). A token of achievement based on your time at the sea. 

This is chest design is twist on traditional American sailor tattoos. The client who is currently actively serving in the navy requested crossed cannons, a nautical star and two swallows. From there I took his ideas and designed a black and grey modern version with filigree and asymmetrical swallows (adding the birds on our next session). 

A chest piece this size 20x12” (51x31cm) usually takes me 2-4 sessions depending on the design and amount of details. When starting a larger size design, the first session often seems shorter due to the need to resize and shape the design to fit the body. After the first session the new shape and size has been determined meaning that the flllowing session have a quick start. 

For all booking inquiries and questions please email me and my assistant Eryn at Sara.Fabel.Tattoo@gmail.com

When fresh and healed tattoos collide. White tiger with cherry blossoms. Tiger fully healed and settled for few weeks. My client had minor sunburn prior to coming for her second session to fill in the flowers. Her existing skin irritation led in to more red than normal end result. This redness will fade as the tattoo heals and in her case won’t affect end result. 

It is up to the artist to determine whether or not clients skin is in good enough condition to be tattooed. Skin conditions that can affect tattoo quality and safety can range from sunburn, rash and scarring, all the way to external factors such a pre-applied numbing creams. Why numbing creams? Because when applied for long periods of time and wrapped in plastic, the skin gathers more moisture and can become rubbery. This makes tattooing the skin harder and often resulting in bad healing. If you are concerned about your skin health or medical conditions that might affect the end quality, always reach out to your artist and have an honest conversation of risk factors relating to your tattoo. 

And please, send your artist healed pictures of your tattoos. We would love to post them to show redness isn’t permanent. 🤍 @bishoprotary bishop wand and @davincineedles 0603rl with @hustlebutterdeluxe CBD cream to help calm the skin. Tattooed at @vaticanstudios_oc California.

I have started generating majority of my reference images via AI. Why? Because I keep seeing same statues, flowers, faces and animals being reused time after time. This is where artificial intelligence comes to rescue.

From there I will manually create my own art. This means that I still take time to sit down and individually cut, copy, paste, blend and design. It is my own world of creating art with designs I have put my mind and artistic intentions to. 

I hear so many arguments towards using and avoiding AI art. What are your thoughts on it? Where do we draw the limit between art without soul?

I rate peek in to unfinished projects and comparison to healed versus fresh tattoos. 

There is 4 year difference between my clients left and right leg tattoos. We started on the left side prior to the pandemic and have progressed to be few sessions away from finishing his right leg.

To avoid redness I use @hustlebutterdeluxe CBD cream which solves the issue of skin irritation. Unfortunate for my client he is unable to use CBD products due to work which means that we have to roll with the redness. This is also why I have been shy posting progress photos as the mixture of healed versus fresh can be disorienting to the viewer.

Don’t be scared of the red! Some people get more red than others and can find the pink glow on a fresh tattoo unnerving. The lightest of light shades often tend to have the most visible glow of “irritation”. Don’t be worried, the redness will mellow out in a day or two and when healed these areas have a subtle beautiful light grey detailing. As a tattooer my main goal is a long lasting end result, not capturing good pictures for the gram. 

If you have healed tattoos I’ve done please email me pictures of them. I would love to post more healed work.
